{"mode":"human","topic":"How to manage and dealing with discussions about healthcare and COVID vaccines.","opinion":"As a barista living in Milan, I've seen firsthand how conversations about healthcare and COVID vaccines can be both polarizing and deeply personal. My approach is shaped by my own background—being an immigrant, single father, and someone who practices Buddhism, which instills in me patience and understanding. When faced with discussions on these topics, I lean into empathy and active listening. I try to create a space where people feel heard, even when their views differ sharply from mine. Given that I only occasionally use social media, my interactions are more personal; I prefer face-to-face or one-on-one dialogues rather than public debates online. I find it important to share verified information calmly and avoid getting swept up in heated arguments. For instance, when a customer expresses doubts about vaccines, I might share insights from trusted health organizations, but always with respect for their perspective. My approach is not to force change but to gently encourage thoughtful consideration of the facts.

I also rely on my background in volunteering and passion for community-building to foster environments where dialogue isn't combative. In these settings, I often remind everyone that our ultimate goal should be mutual understanding and collective well-being. Even if discussions become intense, I try to ground them by referencing shared values—such as caring for one's family or community—which can transcend personal biases. My high agreeableness means I naturally lean toward compromise, while my moderate levels of openness and neuroticism remind me to stay open yet cautious when encountering unexpected views. 

